# MEMORANDUM OF ASSOCIATION OF NEXORA TECHNOLOGY PRIVATE LIMITED COMPANY (PLC)

## ARTICLE ONE: FORMATION
Nexora Technology Private Limited Company (hereinafter referred to as "the Company") is hereby established by the founders whose signatures are affixed at the end of this document, in accordance with Article 495 of the New Commercial Code of Ethiopia, Proclamation No. 1243/2013 (2021). The Company shall be governed by this Memorandum of Association and the objectives set forth in Article Four.

## ARTICLE TWO: NAME, NATIONALITY, AND ADDRESS OF MEMBERS
| No. | Member Name | Nationality | City/Region | Sub-City | Woreda | House No. |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 1 | Ato Haile Debele Bayisa | Ethiopian | Oromia/Adama | Bole | Dadacha Arara | New |
| 2 | Ato Yonas Ayele Tola| Ethiopian | Addis Ababa | Arada | 09 | New |

## ARTICLE THREE: NAME AND HEAD OFFICE
3.1. The name of the company is **NEXORA TECHNOLOGY PLC**.
3.2. The registered Head Office of the Company shall be in Addis Ababa. While the right of members to open branches elsewhere in Ethiopia or abroad is reserved, the current registered office is located in Addis Ababa.

## ARTICLE FOUR: BUSINESS OBJECTIVES
The objectives for which the Company is established are:
1. To design, develop, and deliver high-quality mobile, web, desktop, and cloud-based software applications.
2. To provide innovative digital solutions that enable organizations to improve efficiency, productivity, and performance.
3. To conduct research, development, and implementation of advanced technologies including Artificial Intelligence (AI), Machine Learning (ML), Data Analytics, and Intelligent Systems.
4. To design, develop, and manage scalable and secure database systems, software platforms, and digital infrastructure.
5. To provide software consulting, system architecture design, and digital transformation services.
6. To develop automation systems and digital platforms that support modern business operations.
7. To provide software maintenance, upgrades, technical support, and system integration services.
8. To develop data management systems, information systems, and digital platforms for better information handling and decision-making.
9. To conduct research and innovation related to emerging technologies in the Information Technology sector.
10. To design and develop digital tools and platforms that enhance communication, productivity, and collaboration.
11. To provide professional training, technical knowledge transfer, and capacity building in software development and IT.
12. To develop and manage digital products and services that support the digital economy.
13. To collaborate with government and private organizations in developing and implementing digital systems.
14. To participate in technology innovation, product development, and digital entrepreneurship initiatives.
15. To perform any lawful activities related to software development, IT services, and digital innovation.

## ARTICLE FIVE: CAPITAL
The capital of the Company is **20,000.00 ETB (Twenty Thousand Ethiopian Birr)**, fully paid in cash by the members. The total capital is divided into **20 shares**, each having a par value of **1,000.00 ETB**.

The shareholding distribution is as follows:
| No. | Name of Founding Member | No. of Shares | Unit Price | Total Contribution |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 1 | Ato Haile Debele Baysa | 10 | 1,000 | 10,000.00 |
| 2 | Ato Yonas Ayele Tola | 10 | 1,000 | 10,000.00 |
| | **Total** | **20** | - | **20,000.00** |

## ARTICLE SIX: LIABILITY OF MEMBERS
The members have jointly and severally confirmed that the capital mentioned above is fully paid in cash. Accordingly, the liability of the members shall be limited to the value of their shareholding in the Company.

## ARTICLE SEVEN: PROFIT AND LOSS DISTRIBUTION
Unless otherwise agreed by the members, the annual net profit—after deducting legal reserves and other general expenses—shall be distributed among members according to their shareholding. Losses, if any, shall be shared in the same manner.

## ARTICLE EIGHT: MANAGEMENT
The Company shall be managed by a General Manager appointed from among the members or externally for an indefinite term.
Accordingly, **Ato Haile Debele Baysa** is appointed as the first General Manager, and **Ato Yonas Ayele Tola** is appointed as the Deputy Manager. In the absence of the General Manager, the Deputy Manager shall fully assume the powers and duties of the General Manager.

**Powers and Duties of the Manager(s):**
8.1. Managers may be re-elected; however, members have the power to remove a manager at any time.
8.2. Appoint, remove, and supervise sectoral managers.
8.3. Sign on behalf of the Company.
8.4. Receive funds, pay debts, prepare and endorse bills of exchange, bank documents, and certify commercial documents.
8.5. Responsible for technical and administrative functions.
8.6. Hire/fire employees, determine salaries and bonuses.
8.7. Decide on purchases and sales necessary for business operations.
8.8. Enter into contracts with third parties regarding business transactions.
8.9. Represent the Company in court as plaintiff, defendant, or intervenor, and appoint legal counsel.
8.10. Ensure proper bookkeeping (income/expense) for member approval; delegate powers to third parties when necessary.
8.11. Provide or reclaim CPOs in the Company's name.
8.12. Participate in various tenders.
8.13. Rent or lease property and sign lease agreements.
8.14. Open bank accounts, deposit/withdraw money, sign and process checks.
8.15. Sell or exchange movable/immovable property based on minutes, and borrow money with or without collateral.
8.16. Sign loan and mortgage agreements with private or government banks and micro-finance institutions.
8.17. Purchase movable/immovable property and transfer titles to the Company's name.
8.18. Provide Company property as collateral for third-party loans (if agreed).
8.19. Enter into work contracts, buy shares in other companies, and rent offices.
8.20. Process and renew certificates of competency.
8.21. Follow up on matters with governmental and non-governmental offices.
8.22. Return business licenses upon receiving tax/VAT clearance if required.
8.23. Pay taxes and receive clearances/receipts.
8.24. Delegate or revoke powers of attorney.
8.25. Members of the company may also serve as salaried employees.

## ARTICLE NINE: AUDITOR
The Company shall have an auditor(s) appointed by the members.

## ARTICLE TEN: DURATION OF THE COMPANY
The Company is established for an indefinite period of time.

## ARTICLE ELEVEN: TRANSFER OF SHARES
11.1. Shares are freely transferable between members.
11.2. Members have a right of first refusal for share purchases.
11.3. Shares shall not be transferred to third parties unless the member holding 100% (or the required majority) agrees. Priority is given to existing members via an internal bidding process.
11.4. Share prices shall be determined by mutual agreement.

## ARTICLE TWELVE: PRINCIPLES OF SHARE TRANSFER
12.1. A member wishing to transfer shares must notify the Manager in writing with full identity details.
12.2. Transfer to 3rd parties is allowed only when legal and regulatory requirements are met.
12.3. The Manager shall notify other members in writing within one month of receiving such a request.
12.4. These restrictions do not apply to transfers to heirs; heirs assume the rights and obligations of the deceased member.

## ARTICLE THIRTEEN: RIGHTS AND DUTIES OF MEMBERS
13.1. Each member has the right to:
   a. Participate in all member meetings.
   b. Vote in proportion to their shareholding.
   c. Inspect financial records, profit/loss statements, and audit reports.
13.2. The Company recognizes only one owner per share. If a share is jointly owned, one representative must be appointed. Ownership of a share implies adherence to this Memorandum and the decisions of the general meeting.

## ARTICLE FOURTEEN: RIGHT TO INFORMATION
Any shareholder has the right to read or take copies of the following documents from the head office:
a) Balance sheets, profit and loss statements.
b) Reports of managers and auditors from the last three fiscal years.
c) Minutes of meetings and other supporting documents.

## ARTICLE FIFTEEN: REMUNERATION
The salary, allowances, and benefits of the General Manager and Deputy Manager shall be determined by the members.

## ARTICLE SIXTEEN: MEETINGS AND DECISION MAKING
A quorum is reached when members (or legal proxies) representing more than 75% of the shares are present. Decisions are made by a majority vote based on shareholding.
16.1. An annual general meeting must be held within four months of the end of the fiscal year. Notice must be given 24 days in advance.
16.2. The Manager, Auditor, or members holding >75% of shares may call a meeting at any time.
16.3. 100% agreement is required to change the nature of the company or decrease capital. 75% agreement is sufficient to increase capital, change the name, or merge/dissolve.

## ARTICLE SEVENTEEN: FISCAL YEAR AND PROFIT DISTRIBUTION
17.1. The fiscal year runs from **Hamle 1 to Sene 30** (July 8 - July 7). The first year starts from the date of registration.
17.2. The Manager prepares the annual inventory and financial reports.
17.3. 5% of annual net profits must be set aside as a legal reserve until the reserve reaches 10% of the Company's capital.

## ARTICLE EIGHTEEN: POWERS OF THE GENERAL MEETING
1. Approve the General Manager's report.
2. Review audit reports and take necessary actions.
3. Appoint or remove the General Manager for cause.
4. Issue directives to the General Manager.
5. Decide on the expansion or dissolution of the Company.
6. Decide on the distribution of annual profits.

## ARTICLE NINETEEN: AUDITOR
19.1. The Company shall have a certified auditor (individual or firm).
19.2. Fees are determined by members.
19.3. The auditor reports to the general meeting and has the right to inspect all documents and attend meetings.

## ARTICLE TWENTY: DISSOLUTION
20.1. The Company is not dissolved by the incapacity, bankruptcy, or death of a member.
20.2. Upon dissolution, a third-party liquidator shall be appointed.
20.3. The liquidator will settle debts and distribute remaining assets to members based on their shares.

## ARTICLE TWENTY-ONE: AMENDMENTS
Members may amend this Memorandum of Association at any time in accordance with the Commercial Code.

## ARTICLE TWENTY-TWO: DISPUTE RESOLUTION
Any disputes between members regarding the Company shall be resolved according to the Ethiopian Civil Code and Procedure. Decisions shall be binding and final.

## ARTICLE TWENTY-THREE: EFFECTIVE DATE
This Memorandum shall be effective from the date of its legal approval and registration.

## ARTICLE TWENTY-FOUR: TERM OF SERVICE
The Company is established for an indefinite duration.

